review_blob: Bottle from ABC. Pours a golden amber with a thin head and some really nice lacing. Very strong floral aromas; pine and citrus as well. Very bitter taste throughout - the pine really comes through here. Pretty light-bodied and dry on the finish, which doesnt stick around very long. Solid overall. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a gorgeous and sparkling orange amber with a robust frothy head. Super strong hop aromas - grass, floral, citrus. Taste follows suit - very sweet, slightly bitter, and maybe some faint bread malt that I missed on the nose. Medium-bodied and somewhat dry on the finish. Third or fourth time having this beer and it remains a top-tier IPA for me. Acquire.

Bottle from 711. Pours a sparkling clear gold with a beautiful frothy head and some nice lacing. Aromas are super bright fruits - grapefruit, orange, lemon, with some strong floral notes and a very faint malt backbone. Taste is bitter throughout with a long, dry finish. Light-bodied but extremely heavy on the flavor. Much better than I anticipated. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a nearly pitch black with a thin brown head. Lacing is nice as well. Malt aroma for days; burnt molasses, straw, dark bread. A doughy yeast backbone, it seems. Taste is sweet - vanilla and caramel with strong oak flavors and some pretty well-hidden booze. Body is incredibly full with an almost syrupy texture. The alcohol really comes through on the finish. Beginning to really like this beer. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a muddy brown with minimal head and very thin lacing. Im not sure if its because of how long Ive had it, but the particles are insane. Super citrus aroma with an equally strong floral backbone; some caramel malt as well. Taste is extremely sweet, light on the palate, and creamy on the finish. As always, very refreshing, and one of the best amber ales Ive had. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a murky orange with almost no head at all and some very thin lacing. Aromas are pretty basic - bright fruits, pine, grass. Taste is pretty bitter and matches the nose accordingly. Really thin bodied, dry, and pretty unmemorable, though not a total misstep. Probably refreshing after a rough day. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a very dark brown with almost no head or lacing. Aromas are strong malts - toffee, caramel, molasses. Some dark fruits as well, with a solid yeast backbone. Really quite complex on the nose. Taste is sweet, full bodied, and long on the finish; quite boozy as well. Pretty creamy on the way down. Acquire.

Draft from the Abbey. Pours a very dark brown, borderline black with minimal head and some decent lacing. Strong malt aroma; caramel, cocoa, maybe some vanilla backbone. Taste is quite sweet with a full body and long oily finish. More goodness from Terrapin. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from The Abbey. Pours a very dark brown with an off-white head that lingers for a bit; thin on the lacing. Aromas are very dark fruits and a pretty strong malt backbone. The yeast comes through on the taste, which is quite boozy and very full bodied. Long finish, really good beer. Acquire.

Draft from The Abbey. Pours a hazy gold with a small white head and some very thin lacing. Aromas are bright hops with a slight yeast backbone. Taste is mostly bitter, pretty thin bodied, and dry on the finish. Really quite good overall, though. Acquire 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from ABC. Pours an almost reddish brown with a medium white head and some strong lacing with some visible particles as well. Aroma is typical IPA fare - earth, floral, pine, and a nice malt balance. Taste is pretty sweet throughout and short on the finish; the malt comes through more than anything. Pretty dry going down and underwhelming on the whole, but not too bad for what it is. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a dark muddy brown with a small off-white head and some decent lacing. More malt than hops on the aroma; mostly toasted & nutty flavors. Some dark fruits come through on the hops, and maybe some light floral notes. Taste is pretty bitter all the way through with a short, somewhat dry finish. Not what I typically look for in an IPA, but a decent beer nonetheless. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a shimmering gold with a frothy, bright white head; very full and lasts throughout. Lacing is excellent. Love the small visible particles, too. Aromas are overwhelmingly citrus, pine, floral. Almost a lemon taste; not very bitter at all, and smooth all the way down. Pretty thin and dry on the finish, but really enjoyable overall. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a murky brown with a medium off-white head. Lacing is pretty thin. Aromas are strong floral, pine, citrus. Taste follows suit, but some malt backbone comes through as well. Pretty sweet and somewhat sour on the way down; a pretty oily finish. Full bodied and quite enjoyable overall. Acquire.
beer_name: Uinta Detour Double India Pale Ale

review_blob: Bottle from ABC. Pours a hazy gold with a frothy white head that sticks around - some great lacing as well. A little surprised by how nice this looks, actually, as its my first time having it from the bottle. Aromas are pretty standard for a light IPA - pine, citrus, earth. Taste is pretty sweet and smooth overall with a light body and somewhat dry finish. Never blown away by this, but its certainly not bad at all. Acquire.

Draft from Half Wall. Pours a hazy gold with a thin head and minimal lacing. Aromas are spice & herb, with a very similar taste. Some booze on the finish; nice and full bodied, pretty oily. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from ABC. Pours a perfect hazy golden amber with a small white head and some serious lacing. This is a beautiful beer, particularly this year. Aromas are hoppy as ever - pine, citrus, grass, floral. Taste is incredible well balanced; sweet, a little bitter, and very smooth. Texture is creamy, body is pretty full, and the finish is long. A favorite at this point. Acquire.

Bottle from Publix. Pours a very clear gold with a super thin, quickly dissipating head and little to no lacing. Aromas are very earthy hops - mostly grass & floral. Taste is bitter and dry, though really quite smooth on the way down. Pretty thin bodied but the flavor lingers nicely. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Sierra Nevada Beer Camp Hoppy Lager

review_blob: Bottle from ABC. Pours a dark muddy brown with a thin off-white head with some fantastic lacing. Aromas are light roasted malts and some citrus hops - mostly orange, which comes through very nicely on the taste. Really sweet throughout with a nice long finish; pretty full bodied and oily. Quite good. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a sparkling gold with very nice head and some serious lacing. Aromas are floral, pine, grass, and citrus. Taste is rather bitter with a classic hop character and a very long, creamy finish. Full-bodied and extremely satisfying. Acquire.
beer_name: Victory Hop Ranch Imperial India Pale Ale

review_blob: Bottle from ABC. Pours a dark amber with a thin to medium white head. Lacing is minimal. Aromas are grass, pine, citrus. Taste follows suit but also with some vague malts - mostly bread. Mouthful is surprisingly full with a really oily texture and a long finish. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a clear sparkling gold with a medium white head and some decent lacing; both stick around quite nicely. Aromas are full of citrus with a slight bread malt backbone. Taste is pretty sweet throughout with a pretty short, dry finish. A decent pale ale, no doubt, but nothing more. Acquire.

Can from the Abbey. Pours a murky golden amber with a thin head and almost no lacing. Vague malt aromas with a slightly boozy taste. Body is very light with a pretty dry, empty finish. Not at all enjoyable. Avoid. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Fat Cat Shawshanks Injunction Pale Ale

review_blob:
Draft from The Abbey. Pours a dark golden orange with a medium head and some nice lacing. Smells are extremely fruity - mostly orange. Taste follows suit with a very sweet mouthfeel and super watery & quick finish. Very refreshing and suitable for any time of year, really. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from The Abbey. Pours a semi-clear golden amber. Really nice frothy head and even better lacing. Aroma is light fruits, taste is much of the same; some citrus and banana. Medium body with a very nice creamy finish. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from ABC. Pours a clear gold with a thin white head that disappears almost instantly. Lacing is nice, aroma is very earthy - grass, floral, herbs. Taste is slightly bitter, body is thin, and the finish is a little dry. A solid and refreshing IPA that never really disappoints, but never leaves me wanting more, either. Acquire.

Draft from The Abbey in DeLand, FL. Pours a murky dark brown with a medium, lengthy off-white head. Some really great lacing. Aroma is super piney with some light citrus notes. Taste is quite sweet, somewhat bitter, and the
finish is long and dry. Pretty light-bodied overall and super enjoyable. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Boulder Beer Slope Style Winter IPA

review_blob:
500mL from The Abbey in DeLand, FL. Pours a murky golden orange with a thin white head; really nice lacing. Bright fruit aromas - mostly citrus. Some light earthy notes as well. Taste is quite sweet, somewhat watery, and thin on the finish. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from ABC. Pours a murky golden amber with almost no head and some very thin lacing. Aroma is very fruity, mostly (obviously) mango. Taste is super sweet - almost like flat champagne. Body is very light, thin, with a super dry and lightly carbonated finish. Overall, pretty enjoyable, with a very well-hidden abv. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours an ugly dark brown with an off-white, medium head; some nice lacing, at least. Aromas are mostly malt - molasses, toffee, light rum. Taste is mostly sweet, kind of sour. Light to medium bodied with a creamy finish. Not very enjoyable overall. Avoid.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a muddy, dark brown with a medium off-white, brownish head that sticks around forever. Lacing clings to the glass beautifully. Aroma is deep, dark malts; toasted nuts, bread, molasses, toffee. An initial almost sour flavor gives way to a rather creamy, sweet finish. Long, thick, full-bodied throughout. Acquire.

Can from ABC. Pours a murky orange with a medium frothy white head that disappears pretty quickly. Lacing is very thin. Aroma and taste are both fruity with a vague yeast backbone; the orange flavor is noticeable throughout. A pretty dry, thin finish, but incredibly refreshing on this 82 degree Florida "winter" day. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Cigar City Florida Cracker White Ale

review_blob: 16oz can from ABC. Pours a murky golden orange with virtually no head and very little lacing. Hoppy aromas - pine, grass, light cirtrus; some vague malt as well, perhaps a light bread. Taste is bitter with a creamy, full texture. A pretty short, almost flat finish. A decent IIPA overall, but nothing to set it apart other than the hilariously bad can art. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a hazy golden orange with a thin, very brief head. Decent lacing. Wonderful aromas of dark fruits, maybe some grains as well. Taste is pretty sweet throughout with a long lasting and somewhat boozy finish; the rum comes through at the very end. Very drinkable with a deceptive ABV, Id say. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a clear golden with a super thin head that actually sticks around for a bit; some good lacing as well. Aroma is very earthy; pines, citrus, grass. Taste is pretty damn sweet with a medium body and somewhat metallic finish. Packs quite a punch, in the best way. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a perfect, shimmering golden amber with a frothy white head and ample lacing. Smells of floral, citrus, herbs, with an earthy backbone and some lingering malt. Flavor is bitter and somewhat sweet throughout. Full bodied, creamy, and smooth on the finish; taste lingers, and it is wonderful. A long time, all-time favorite. Acquire.

Can from ABC. Pours a gorgeous golden orange with a massive, frothy off-white head that sticks around and fantastic lacing. Smells of bread, floral, grass, pine, and citrus; a wonderfully light amalgam of each. Taste is bitter throughout with a long, creamy, extremely nice finish. The abv would have fooled me, because this is an extremely smooth IIPA. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a clear golden orange with a thin head and some pretty nice lacing. Aroma is citrus, obviously mostly orange and with a huge alcohol overtone. Taste is extremely boozy to the point of overpowering what could be a nice flavor. Mouthfeel is very oily with a very bitter, astringent finish. I get the idea behind this beer but it just doesnt really work at all for me. Avoid.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a wonderful hazy gold with a decent head and really nice lacing. Aromas of citrus and bread. Sweet taste throughout with a pretty dry finish; medium body with a lingering, light bitterness. Quite refreshing overall. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a medium golden brown with a thin, quickly disappearing head and almost no lacing. Aroma is mostly malt; nutty and toasty. Maybe some yeasty leather as well. Flavor is pretty sweet throughout with a dry feel and boozy finish. Not a fantastic rye, but not bad, either. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a beautiful hazy amber with a perfect frothy head and some great lacing as well. Aromas are a glorious combination of pine, citrus, and flower. Taste is sweet at first with a strong bitter finish with staying power. Mouthfeel is medium to full bodied, creamy and utterly satisfying. This has been my favorite beer for years, now, and Sierra Nevada once again have reminded me why. Ill be stocking up soon. Acquire.

Bottle from ABC. Pours a hazy/murky gold with a medium head that slowly dissipates, though not entirely. Very noticeable particles. Not much lacing to speak of. Aroma is surprisingly fruity; mostly lemon, hints of yeast. Taste is rather sweet, somewhat dry on the finish. Light bodied and overall refreshing. Acquire. ---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from ABC. Pours a beautiful dark golden amber with a thin head and almost no lacing. Aroma is equal parts fruit and nut, with the peach really coming through. Taste is very light, thin, and smooth; carbonation is pretty high. Very light-bodied with a surprisingly nice finish and aftertaste. A solid winter brew. Acquire. ---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from ABC. Pours a dark murky orange with a very thin head that's gone almost instantly; surprisingly good lacing, though. Aromas of flowers, grass, pine, and maybe some orange as well. Very sweet on the tongue and on the way down. Light body, considering the abv, and even a somewhat watery finish. Very drinkable and refreshing. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from ABC. Pours a gorgeous dark murky brown with a thin head that is gone almost instantly. Lacing is expectedly thin as well. Aroma is super piney with a malt skeleton. Some dark fruits here as well. Flavor is bitter throughout with a long, satisfying finish. Full bodied, oily mouthfeel. Each sip is a glorious jolt of flavor and a reminder of why I love this style. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from ABC. Pours a super dark amber with a very large, frothy head. Smells of fruit are immediate, banana being the most apparent; maybe some darker fruits as well. Lacing is wonderful and almost layered after every sip. Flavor is mostly sweet throughout, medium bodied and a little dry on the finish. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Can from ABC (for a dollar!?). Pours a beautiful hazy orange with a perfect, frothy white head that stays. Lacing is wonderful as well. Aroma is a glorious amalgam of pine, citrus, and floral notes. Flavor is mostly sweet with a little bitterness on the way down and thereafter. Light body, creamy feel. An all time favorite. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Cigar City Jai Alai India Pale Ale

review_blob:
Bottle from ABC. Pours a golden orange with a thin white head that disappears immediately. Almost no lacing. Smells of strong citrus, mostly oranges. Very watery but the taste isn't bad at all despite being thin and pretty unmemorable. Good for warm sunny days but not much else. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from ABC. Pours a hazy golden amber with a thin, quickly vanishing white head. Strong hop aroma, mostly grass with hints of citrus, maybe some raisin. Taste is somewhat bitter but sticks around well after the finish. I've heard good things and am not at all disappointed. Acquire. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Boulevard Smokestack Series - Tank 7 Farmhouse Ale

review_blob:
Bottle from ABC. Pours a beautiful hazy orange with a thin white head. Shards of fruit floating around. Wonderful fruity aroma of apples and oranges. Taste is extremely smooth and thin. Very sweet with a quick finish. One of the best fruit beers I've had. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
